SIMPLE: grow
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Grow
<hw>Grow</hw> <pr>(gr⟦omac⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Grew</conjf> <pr>(gr⟦udd⟧)</pr>; <pos>p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Grown </conjf> <pr>(gr⟦omac⟧n)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Growing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>gr⟦omac⟧wan</ets>; akin to D. <ets>groeijen</ets>, Icel.
<ets>gr⟦omac⟧a</ets>, Dan. <ets>groe</ets>, Sw. <ets>gro</ets>. Cf.
<er>Green</er>, <er>Grass</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To increase in
size by a natural and organic process; to increase in bulk by the
gradual assimilation of new matter into the living organism; -- said of
animals and vegetables and their organs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To increase in any way; to become larger and
stronger; to be augmented; to advance; to extend; to wax; to
accrue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Winter began to <qex>grow</qex> fast on.</q>
<rj><qau>Knolles.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Even just the sum that I do owe to you⟦br⟧
Is <qex>growing</qex> to me by Antipholus.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To spring up and come to maturity in a natural way;
to be produced by vegetation; to thrive; to flourish; <as>as, rice
<ex>grows</ex> in warm countries</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where law faileth, error <qex>groweth</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Gower.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To pass from one state to another; to result as an
effect from a cause; to become; <as>as, to <ex>grow</ex>
pale</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For his mind⟦br⟧
Had <qex>grown</qex> Suspicion's sanctuary.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To become attached or fixed; to adhere.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our knees shall kneel till to the ground they <qex>grow</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><mcol><col><b>Growing cell</b></col>, or <col><b>Growing
slide</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a device for preserving alive a minute
object in water continually renewed, in a manner to permit its growth to
be watched under the microscope.</cd> -- <col><b>Grown over</b></col>,
<cd>covered with a growth.</cd> -- <col><b>To grow out of</b></col>,
<cd>to issue from, as plants from the soil, or as a branch from the main
stem; to result from.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These wars have <qex>grown out of</qex> commercial
considerations.</q> <rj><qau>A. Hamilton. </qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>To grow up</b></col>, <cd>to arrive at full stature or
maturity; as, <ex>grown up</ex> children.</cd> -- <col><b>To grow
together</b></col>, <cd>to close and adhere; to become united by growth,
as flesh or the bark of a tree severed.</cd>
<rj><au>Howells.</au></rj></p></cs>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To become; increase; enlarge; augment; improve;
expand; extend.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Grow
<hw>Grow</hw> <pr>(gr⟦omac⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause to
grow; to cultivate; to produce; <as>as, to <ex>grow</ex> a crop; to
<ex>grow</ex> wheat, hops, or tobacco.</as></def>
<rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To raise; to cultivate. See <er>Raise</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos>, 3.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Growable</ent>⟦br⟧
